{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01XQqqUHaniKLByaunmf1p3p","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior carefully using the framework provided.\n\n**Behavior 1: The embedding vector produced for a given query string has the correct dimensionality for the vector database index.**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This is about the embedding model producing vectors of the right dimension. Is this about module interaction or a single function's output? The embedding model produces the vector, and the vector database expects a certain dimension. The failure could appear when the embedding output is passed to the vector DB — but the dimensionality check itself is a property of what the embedding model returns. You could check this with just the embedding model alone.\n- REAL-INFRA: Does it depend on real network/OS? If using a real embedding API (like OpenAI embeddings), yes — system level. \n\nBut testing the actual dimensionality of the output requires calling the real embedding model to get a genuine vector and verify its shape, since a mock would just return whatever we programmed it to return. Dimensionality is deterministic for a given model, so this isn't about quality or LLM variability — it's purely about the output shape. If we mock the embedding model, we'd bypass the actual test entirely and just confirm our mock works, so we need the real embedding model to validate what it actually produces.\n\nThe question is which embedding model we're dealing with. If it's a local one like sentence-transformers, an integration test might work fine without real HTTP calls. But given the context of a REST API and vector database, this is probably an external service like OpenAI, which would require hitting the real API. Though here's the thing — embedding model dimensionality is a fixed property of the model itself. If we know the model returns a specific dimension, we could theoretically mock that, but that's circular reasoning since we're just testing what we hardcoded. The real risk this test guards against is the embedding model returning an unexpected dimension due to a version change or wrong model being used. System is the right level because embedding models are typically external services, and even local models loaded from disk represent real infrastructure that a fake can't replicate—a mock would hide the actual dimensionality mismatch that only surfaces with real model output. Agentic doesn't apply here since dimensionality is deterministic, not dependent on LLM non-determinism. a real AI/ML model call (e.g., classification, scoring, generation APIs)\". Embedding is an AI/ML model call. But the test is about dimensionality — which is deterministic. The model always returns the same dimension. So this is System (real API call) not Agentic.\n\nHmm, but if it's an external API call, that's System. If local model, Integration.\n\nI'll go with System, with REJECTION-GATE noting that Agentic is disqualified because the dimensionality of the output is deterministic, not dependent on model quality/non-determinism.\n\nActually, let me reconsider one more time. The embedding model IS an AI/ML model. Even if it's deterministic in terms of dimension, the call itself goes to a real AI/ML model. But the test is checking dimensionality, which could be verified by calling the real model once and checking the vector length against the expected dimension. This is a System test — whether it's an external HTTP call or loading a local model, we're validating against real infrastructure, not testing quality variations. So System it is for Behavior 1.\n\nNow for Behavior 2, I'm thinking about the similarity search ordering. If I mock the vector database, I can control what results come back and in what order, but then I'm not actually testing whether the real vector database returns results sorted by descending cosine similarity. For this to be a meaningful test, I need either the real vector database or at least a real in-process implementation that actually computes similarities.\n\nIf the vector database is local (FAISS, embedded Qdrant), I can test the ordering behavior without external HTTP calls — that's Integration. But if it's a cloud service like Pinecone or Weaviate Cloud, I'd need System-level testing with real HTTP. Given that vector databases can typically run locally for testing purposes, Integration seems appropriate here with a real local vector database that actually performs the similarity computation and ordering.\n\nFor Behavior 3, the LLM re-ranking step depends on the actual LLM's reasoning and output — whether it genuinely reorders results based on nuanced query intent. This is fundamentally an LLM dependency, not something I can mock away without hiding the real behavior.\n\nFor Behavior 4, I'm now looking at whether queries with no close matches return empty results instead of low-relevance noise.\n\nThis is really about the embedding model, vector DB, and filtering working together — a module interaction problem where the system needs to apply a threshold to filter out low-similarity results. I could test this with a real or in-memory vector DB loaded with pre-existing vectors that don't match the test query, checking that results below the threshold get filtered out. The core question is whether correctness depends on the LLM — the filtering logic itself is deterministic and doesn't require LLM output, though re-ranking might happen downstream. I could mock the vector DB to return low scores and verify the filtering logic works, which would be a unit test approach.\n\nBut actually, this feels more like an integration test since I'm checking whether multiple modules — the embedding step, vector search, and result filtering — correctly handle the no-match case together. An in-process vector DB with test data that has no close matches would catch this failure. For the integration brake check: I don't need real OS or network with a local vector DB, and while the embedding model ideally produces a real vector, I could use a deterministic test embedding since the key behavior is whether low-similarity results get filtered. There's no multiple agentic steps involved here.\n\nThe tricky part is whether I need real infrastructure for actual similarity scores. If I pre-load the vector DB with known vectors and use a test query vector that's far from all of them, I can deterministically trigger the \"no close matches\" scenario without real embeddings. So this is definitely integration-level testing.\n\nActually, the re-ranking step is a red herring here — if the similarity search returns nothing below the threshold, re-ranking never happens anyway. The behavior really hinges on the filtering at the similarity search level, not downstream. This isn't purely a unit test of the filtering logic in isolation; it's about how that logic integrates with the search results. So integration it is.\n\nNow for Behavior 5 about end-to-end latency from query to response...\n\nEnd-to-end latency requires everything to run at realistic speeds — embedding API calls, vector DB queries, LLM re-ranking, all the HTTP round trips. Mocks would be instant and useless for measuring real latency. The full pipeline from embedding through re-ranking to response is involved, and the LLM component especially contributes variable latency. This is a system-level test that needs real infrastructure and real network calls to validate the median case performance. The real-time latency measurements from actual services introduce non-deterministic timing that's inherent to the AI/ML calls themselves, not just infrastructure delays. This pushes it toward Workflow rather than System—the distinction being that System focuses on infrastructure dependencies like HTTP and subprocesses, while Workflow captures the agentic multi-step nature where the non-determinism comes from the models themselves. I'm reconsidering whether the embedding dimension check is truly agentic or just a deterministic property of the model.\n\nActually, checking embedding dimensions is deterministic—the model always returns the same dimension—so it's System, not Agentic. But I can't verify the actual configured model's output without calling the real API; a hardcoded assertion wouldn't catch real failures like misconfiguration or model updates. So Behavior 1 is System. Behavior 2 stays Integration since the vector DB and cosine similarity are deterministic. Behavior 3 is Agentic because the LLM's re-ranking quality depends on real model reasoning. Behavior 4 is Integration.\n\nNow I'm assigning probability distributions across test levels for each behavior. For Behavior 1, System gets the highest weight at 0.60 since the real embedding API is needed, with Integration at 0.20 for a possible local model alternative. For Behavior 2, Integration dominates at 0.65 because the vector DB ordering is reproducible locally, though System gets 0.25 if using a cloud vector store.\n\nBehavior 3 is heavily Agentic at 0.80—the LLM quality directly determines whether the reordering works, so mocking won't catch real failures. Behavior 4 splits between Integration at 0.65 for testing the filtering logic with an in-process vector DB, and System at 0.20 if the real vector DB is needed. For Behavior 5, I'm still working through the distribution...\n\nNow I'm checking whether each behavior's evidence level aligns with its output level. Behavior 1 needs a real embedding model, so System testing is appropriate. Behavior 2 can get by with a local vector DB at the Integration level. I should verify the rest follow this same consistency pattern and note any gaps. I'm realizing we could pre-load the vector database with known vectors and use a test query that's guaranteed to be far from all of them, which keeps the test at the Integration level without needing a real embedding model. I'm satisfied with how these behaviors map to their evidence and output levels, so I'm ready to write the final output.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":10129,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":10129},"output_tokens":6,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9fed55d4-42d8-4a3f-8899-b33d93bdcbf7","uuid":"4dba0225-56dc-4eca-a2a1-937308c88bd2"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01XQqqUHaniKLByaunmf1p3p","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_019C9XEELS97vbFaHjVQTzQS","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The embedding vector produced for a given query string has the correct dimensionality for the vector database index.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode (wrong vector dimension) only appears when the real embedding model is called — a mock returns whatever dimension we hardcode, making the test circular. REAL-INFRA: The embedding model is an external API in this architecture; verifying actual output dimensionality requires a real HTTP call to the embedding service. MOCK-HIDE: A stub embedding always returns a pre-shaped vector of whatever dimension we specify, hiding any real misconfiguration (wrong model, model version change, API key pointing to different model). LLM-DEP: Dimensionality is deterministic for a given model — the same model always produces the same vector length regardless of input — so Agentic is disqualified. REJECTION-GATE: Agentic disqualified because 'running this test 100 times gives different outcomes' is false; dimension is a fixed property of the model. COMMIT-TO-REASONING: Evidence points to System; output is System — consistent.","test_description":"Send a real query string to the live embedding API endpoint configured for the application. Assert that the returned vector has exactly the expected dimension (e.g., 1536 for text-embedding-ada-002) matching the vector database index configuration. Run against the real configured embedding service to catch model misconfiguration, API key routing errors, or model version changes.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.04,"Integration":0.18,"System":0.62,"Agentic":0.11,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The similarity search returns results ordered by descending cosine similarity score.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure appears at the boundary between the application's search module and the vector database — if the search call doesn't enforce ordering or misreads the returned order, a mock that pre-returns sorted results hides it. A real (local) vector DB is needed. REAL-INFRA: Cosine similarity ordering is deterministic math; a local in-process vector DB (FAISS, embedded Qdrant, or similar) can fully reproduce the ordering behavior without real network. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking the DB to return pre-sorted results makes the test trivially pass regardless of whether the application actually requests ordered results. LLM-DEP: Cosine similarity is pure math — no AI non-determinism. INTEGRATION-BRAKE: (a) No real OS/network needed — local in-process DB suffices. (b) No AI/ML quality dependency. (c) No multi-step agentic chain. COMMIT-TO-REASONING: Evidence points to Integration; output is Integration — consistent.","test_description":"Pre-populate an in-process vector database (e.g., FAISS or embedded Qdrant) with vectors of known cosine similarities to a test query vector. Issue a similarity search for the test query. Assert that the returned results list is sorted in strictly descending order by the cosine similarity score field. Include at least 5 vectors with known, distinct similarity values to catch partial-ordering bugs.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.25,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The LLM re-ranking step changes the order of at least some results compared to the raw similarity ranking when the query has nuanced intent.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP: The behavior explicitly tests whether the LLM produces contextually aware reordering — this is a quality/reasoning property of the real LLM, not a deterministic function. MOCK-HIDE: A stubbed LLM returning a fixed permutation trivially passes regardless of whether the real LLM understands nuanced intent at all. MOCK-MISS: The failure (LLM fails to reorder when it should) only manifests with a real LLM call; no amount of module wiring tests this. MULTI-STEP: A single LLM re-ranking call, not a multi-step chain — Workflow is disqualified. REJECTION-GATE: Workflow disqualified because behavior describes a single re-ranking step, not 'multiple agentic steps in sequence.' System disqualified because the failure mode is LLM reasoning quality, not infrastructure behavior. COMMIT-TO-REASONING: Evidence points clearly to Agentic; output is Agentic — consistent.","test_description":"Construct a test set of queries with known nuanced intent (e.g., 'lightweight running shoes for wide feet' where semantic similarity ranks a generic running shoe first but contextual relevance should prefer a wide-fit model). Feed raw similarity-ranked results to the real LLM re-ranker. Assert that the re-ranked output is not identical to the input order for at least a meaningful fraction of the test cases. Log both orders to diagnose regressions when LLM behavior changes.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.82,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"A query with no close matches in the database returns an empty result set rather than low-relevance noise.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure lives at the boundary between the vector search module and the result-filtering/threshold logic — a bug could be that the threshold is never applied, or that low-score results leak through. Testing the filtering function alone (Unit) misses wiring bugs where the score from the DB is not correctly forwarded to the filter. REAL-INFRA: A local in-process vector DB pre-loaded with known vectors can reproduce the 'no close matches' scenario deterministically by using a test query vector known to be far from all stored vectors. No real network needed. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking the vector DB to return low-score results tests the filter logic, but hides cases where the score field name/format from the real DB differs from what the filter expects. LLM-DEP: Cosine similarity thresholding is deterministic math. INTEGRATION-BRAKE: (a) No real OS/network. (b) No AI quality dependency — threshold comparison is deterministic. (c) No multi-step agentic chain. COMMIT-TO-REASONING: Evidence points to Integration; output is Integration — consistent.","test_description":"Pre-populate an in-process vector DB with vectors representing a known product catalog. Construct a test query vector that is mathematically distant from all stored vectors (cosine similarity below the configured threshold for all entries). Issue the full search pipeline (embedding lookup → similarity search → threshold filter). Assert that the returned result list is empty. Also assert that no results with similarity below the threshold appear in any intermediate state returned to the caller.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.09,"Integration":0.64,"System":0.22,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The end-to-end latency from receiving the query to returning re-ranked results stays below 2 seconds for the median case.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"MULTI-STEP: The pipeline chains multiple real AI/ML calls in sequence: (1) real embedding API call, (2) real vector DB query, (3) real LLM re-ranking call, (4) HTTP response. This is a full multi-step agentic pipeline. REAL-INFRA: Latency is measured wall-clock time across real network calls — an in-process stub returns in microseconds and hides all real timing. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking any step eliminates its real latency contribution, making the 2-second budget meaningless. LLM-DEP: Both the embedding model and the LLM re-ranker contribute variable latency; real calls are required to measure median behavior. REJECTION-GATE: System disqualified because the SLA depends on coordinated latency of multiple AI/ML model calls (embedding + LLM), not just real HTTP in isolation. Agentic disqualified because the behavior spans multiple sequential AI calls, not a single model call. COMMIT-TO-REASONING: Evidence points to Workflow; output is Workflow — consistent.","test_description":"Send N representative queries (N ≥ 30 for statistical stability) through the full production pipeline: real HTTP to the embedding API, real vector DB query, real LLM re-ranking, full HTTP response returned. Record wall-clock latency for each request. Assert that the p50 (median) latency across all N requests is below 2000ms. Also capture p95 to provide early warning of tail latency creep. Run in an environment with network conditions representative of production.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.02,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.17,"Workflow":0.7}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":10129,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":10129},"output_tokens":6,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9fed55d4-42d8-4a3f-8899-b33d93bdcbf7","uuid":"b2af1232-8501-4124-a0b8-edc2a828118e"}
